@inproceedings{BakerLevelts,
    abstract = {{Exploring how to understand any AAC approach can be aided by insight into the word/language production experience of typical populations. Numerous models of language generation, both serial and constructionist, have been designed and promoted. Such theories typically divide processes into distinctive areas from conceptualization/semantic, lexical/syntactic, phonologic/phonetic, and onto motoric models necessary for articulation. There are various modern word-production models starting with Edward Sapir's Psychological Reality of the Phoneme (1933) to W.J.M. Levelt's serialist approach (1989), and the connectionist approaches described by Dell, Chang, \& Griffin (1999). All of these models understand language production as a word-by-word, function-by-function process with varying degrees of monitoring and feedback. From the field of AAC, itself, the first formal attempt at a model is Lloyd, Quist, \& Windsor (1989) based on Sanders' Aural Rehabilitation (1982). Environmental and gestural issues are present in all face-to-face communications though they are not treated in this paper beyond simple mention. The purpose of the presentation is to examine, speculate, and theorize about the internal linguistic elements of the experiential phenomena of two distinct populations -- typical speakers and augmented speakers. The process of traveling from the concept/preverbal message to the communicative act is discussed. The internal experiential dynamics of lexicon selection and syntax organization will be explored. From there, the authors will theorize further about the internal experiences of two groups of augmented communicators. Video interviews with augmented communicators are shown. The results of these inquiries should be a sharpening of researchers' questions about AAC users' language experiences.}},
