@inproceedings{Fleury2014Enhancing,
    abstract = {{Aim We wish to explore the use of electronic textiles for communication for individuals with severe disabilities through several related projects. The first will investigate a textile-based keyboard, combining the low cost and durability of low tech devices, with the added functions of more expensive technology. In the second, we focus on the problem of involuntary movement which often makes standard AAC devices unusable. We aim to detect functional intention amid hyperkinetic movement to inform existing access technologies. Methods A washable textile-based keyboard with a visual display, for use when more high-tech devices are impractical, has been tested in the lab for durability and usability. Additional features have been implemented, including layout customization and word prediction. For movement monitoring, we have first characterized potential sensor behavior for linear and single joint motion sensing. We will next extend these findings to the measure of full body motion, comparing results to standard movement monitoring technologies. Results Initial prototypes have been simple, fast and inexpensive to construct. Preliminary findings are promising, showing excellent results for durability and sensitivity of textile-based sensors in a variety of applications. Conclusion Although textile-based sensors in rehabilitation have traditionally been used in monitoring applications, they appear to have great potential in communication applications as well. Initial results warrant further research and technology development, with the goal of eventual testing of both technologies presented here with the target population.}},
