@inproceedings{Russell2014Access,
    abstract = {{This session will provide an in-depth look at occupational therapy's approach to the physical access assessment process for children with complex communication needs. The targeted goal of efficient, independent access to active participation in communication, computer use, academics, mobility \& leisure activities guides this approach. This multifaceted assessment process entails collection and synthesis of information relating to each child's unique sensory-motor abilities, vision, hearing, cognition, tone, seating and positioning. Goals for the child as well as environments in which they will be performed also need to be factored into the clinical decision making process. Once direct selection access options have been exhausted, switch access becomes the focus starting with control site identification, switch selection, switch placement and related accommodations resulting in ” functional switch use.” Using a switch for scanning access to communication devices requires considerable user demands and skills. Acquisition and mastery of these skills can be facilitated via a developmental progression of motivating switch activities in which the child builds confidence and success, prior to layering additional cognitive demands of language. Further focus on the progression of switch activities designed to develop motor patterns, success, and automaticity will follow. In-depth discussion of challenges of switch access to AAC devices will be discussed and highlighted through case studies with narrative and video.}},
