@inproceedings{Christensen2014A,
    abstract = {{This study examined the latency and accuracy measurements of five different augmentative and alternative (AAC) iPad applications by measuring the performance of typically developing adults using the apps to complete functional communication tasks. Five apps were selected following a systematic search of the iTunes Store and met inclusion criteria including capability to: synthesize speech, generate utterances using manufacturer-programmed individual whole words, pre-stored phrases, and spelling. Each participant completed ten experimental sessions. In each session, participants completed three functional communication tasks: navigating to a word, spelling a word, and constructing a phrase using manufacturer-programmed individual whole words. Each app was left in its manufacturer-programmed configuration and was not customized or altered. Minimal training was provided to the participants, consisting only of corrective feedback offered during the third session. In the current study, the correlations between the latency measurements and accuracy scores were calculated. The results indicated correlations of +0.66 for spelling tasks and +0.98 for phrase construction tasks. In conclusion, this study found that different apps have different levels of usefulness in word navigation, spelling and phrase construction, depending on the user preference.}},
