@mastersthesis{Bettany2012Could,
    abstract = {{Aided Language Stimulation (ALS) is a communication partner strategy with potential to be used by parents with children with communication disabilities across a range of daily activities. Communication disability can result in low educational achievement, social isolation and reduced ability to live independently. Augmentative and alternative communication (AAC) is used to help people understand and express language, build relationships and access education. Approximately 0.03 -1.4\\ of children use AAC. Abandonment rates are estimated at 30\%. Poorly designed AAC and a lack of communication partner training could be contributing factors to abandonment. Research indicates ALS is potentially effective in schools and clinics. Home intervention has not been investigated. Qualitative studies have shown some parents want more involvement in their children's AAC services and want AAC services at home. Aims: This study aims to investigate whether ALS could be an effective home intervention for AAC-users aged 11-16 by investigating the impact on the communicative competence of parents. Parents' experiences of home intervention would also be investigated. Methods: A mixed methods design was proposed that measured before and after intervention responses to a self-rated questionnaire. Qualitative information would then be gained through focus group interviews with participants. Participants in the study were recruited from a London Special School. Four families were sought. Results: One parent-child pair participated in the study. Participants were withdrawn before completing intervention due to family bereavement. Subjective data indicated the parent was able to implement ALS successfully, bilingually and involve other members of the family. Information from the family's perspective was unavailable. Objective measures of change were also unavailable. Barriers participation in therapy are discussed. The effects of ALS on parents' communicative competence are undetermined. The successful implementation of ALS during the intervention period is encouraging. ALS could be a viable option to supporting children with AAC at home. Submitted in partial fulfilment of the University of London degree, Master of Research in Clinical Practice.}},
