@mastersthesis{Axelsson2013Text,
    abstract = {{People with speech and movement disabilities can use Tobii's eye-tracking products as a communication channel controlled by their eyes. To type with the eyes, gaze typing, is considerably slower than speaking or typing with hands. The purpose of this master thesis is to explore the possibilities of faster gaze typing and to develop a new interface with which it is possible to type faster than with Tobii's standard interface. First we developed a theoretical model with the purpose of evaluating gaze typing interfaces with a special focus on maximum typing speed. While it could serve as a useful set of tools, the existing uncertainties in user properties are limiting the effectiveness of the model. Next we conducted an investigation of word prediction engines that showed that SwiftKey was the most efficient engine in a group of ten. SwiftKey saved in average 29\% entry load in a more extensive evaluation performed. Finally we created a new gaze typing interface prototype, named GazeSwitcher. With practical tests we compared it with Tobii's standard interface (Gaze Selection keyboard) and with a new prototype from Tobii, the Circular keyboard. GazeSwitcher was significant faster than the Circular keyboard in all measurements and also faster than the Gaze Selection keyboard for top-speed results, but not in the overall average. A list of improvement suggestions for these three interfaces is included in the thesis.}},
